The first virtual service provider will reach Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The Czech mobile market is relatively advanced and our service providers provide practically the same services as their Western European partners.
However, there is something missing here - the virtual service provider that forces classical service providers to significantly reduce prices.
Maybe it won't be long.
On Mobile.cz website, we have often written that Czech service providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
This has been confirmed by the ČTO, which has pointed out that the cost of texting in the Czech Republic is more expensive than the other countries of the Union.
Following the last step of the European Commission, roaming charges may thus have a contradictory situation - Czech mobile operators are going to be cheaper than nationals for some customers from abroad.
How can prices in Czech Republic be so high in comparison with Europe?
The answer is simple, I miss the competition that really wants to fight.
This may sound contradictory because we have three mobile networks and our penetration is highly over 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators are pleased to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
This is often agreed by Mr Dvořák, the Chairman of the Czech Telecommunications Office, who has said a few times that there is no place for another service provider in Czech Republic.
Perhaps it is true that the classic service provider is no longer likely to have too many chances on its own network (although it is probably hard to find frequency).
But there is another possibility - the virtual service provider.
It was precisely the move of virtual service providers to the mobile market that led to a significant decrease in prices, which the classic service providers had to respond to.
In the meantime, even before the big fish were placed on the market, such as Tesco Mobile or Virginia Mobile in Great Britain, there were voices similar to ours.
However, it has proven that such providers have a place and can indeed succeed.
However, we do not have to go too far for an example.
This February we informed you about the launch of the Mobilking virtual service provider in Poland.
This service provider has managed to obtain more than 100 000 customers in not only six months and become the fifth largest service provider there.
In the meantime, the Penta Financial Group is behind Mobilking, which is not only the owner of the U:fon in Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual service providers is the possibility of focusing on a much narrower target group.
For effective operation, much less customers than the traditional service provider need.
It does not entail relatively high costs for construction, mobile network operation and maintenance.
Virtual service providers in the world usually show low costs - cheap calls and text messages, which are often offset by less service.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Great Britain offers at least 50 percent cheaper texts than its competitors.
But as the example of Poland's Mobilking shows, it can be a pretty good move to adopt a target group.
This service provider focuses specifically on men.
