Psychology of overbringing: why are we selling more money?
In auctions, customers tend to release more money, overestimate the goods.
This well-known - and seemingly irrational - behavior has developed the neurological-economy foundations for researchers from the University of New York, neurologic and economist.
According to their study in Science magazine, people do not want to go down in a kind of competition such as auctioning eBay, so they will pay too high prices.
The research attempted to map this "play" nervous system through experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers has been lottery, another group has been auctioning, while using the functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) method, the active brain areas of experimental individuals were examined.
In both games, the participants were able to win money, but during the auction game - in which the other party's overbidging is an essential element - the complex called the brain beneath the game was intensively operational when the game was lost.
This brain area plays a role in the mechanism of the nervous system 'supporting' involving several other functions.
Therefore, researchers believe that the price increase can be explained by avoiding the intense reaction of the striatum.
To support their theory, the research team’s economists also carried out a financial follow-up study.
In this three groups bid against a partner under different circumstances.
The control group simply informed the real value of the product and made their bets.
Another group was also promised that if they get out of the game won, they'll be rewarding $15 more.
However, the third group received just $15 before the auction, but the members of the group lost this money in the event of a loss auction.
The difference between the two groups was, therefore, only to one of them the profits and the loss for the other.
However, demonstrating the hypothesis of neurologics, the members of the "deceased" team were willing to make higher stakes than the control and the "fortune" group.
"These results cannot be deducted from any theory of an existing economy.
For the time being, they explained only the phenomenons in auction with the joy of victory and the avoidance of risk.
Only the neurological imaging methods helped to solve the contradiction between these two theories by now gaining a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, professor of the economic faculty of the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should we contact a doctor?
Around half a billion people in the world suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infections, and in Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned among the leading causes of death.
The number of hepatitis-infected people here can be estimated at 100 000, but only seven thousand people are treated for which the patients often don't know that they're infected.
The name of the hepatitis is the collection name of infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
In their symptoms there are many similarities, typical of liver inflammation and yellowness, but their pathogens and caused diseases differ.
hepatitis viruses are spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E through the nutrient channel (e.g. infected food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body wets (swelling, vaginal, saliva).
Travellers should certainly be vaccinated against virus A and B, no vaccine against C.
Hepatitis Symptoms occur two to three weeks after infected food consumption, generally with malaise, weakness, abdominal disorder, nausea.
After this, the yellowness of the skin and the eye protein occurs, the faeces are clear, the urine becomes dark, healing may take two to three weeks.
A million people die worldwide in the more severe type of disease, hepatitis B liver cancers and liver muscles.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only every tenth infected receives pharmaceutical treatment.
Hepatitis C may also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it may also lead to liver suppression, liver cancer.
Most infected people don't even know about their disease because the pathogen destroys the liver cells underwhelmingly, in many cases the first symptoms occur only 20-30 years later.
Thus, early prevention, regular screening tests are very important.
In three groups, such diseases are much more than average: people who have passed blood transfusions before 1991, drug users and tattooed people.
The number of chronic hepatitis C virus infected is currently 200 million in the world.
As a routine laboratory study may indicate the disease, it is appropriate to contact your doctor if you notice any unidentified symptoms.
In time, recognising the disease can be cured, the virus can be removed from the body so that the infectiousness is eliminated and cancer can be prevented.
On 30 September, the World Day of Hepatitis was organised first in 2004 by organisations representing patients worldwide.
It aims to draw attention to chronic liver inflammation, causes of development caused by viruses and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
